  "notes": "Consensus formed by weighting each item by coverage (how many of 10 members hold it) AND conviction, then damping for dispersion. (1) Firmest signals: stablecoins/payments, ai-crypto + agentic-payments, privacy, institutional-adoption, defi, and the network-tokens quality framework \u2014 all high-coverage, low-dispersion, and mutually reinforcing. (2) Most contested item: BTC \u2014 5 members cover it but they genuinely disagree (stance_dispersion 0.98, net slightly negative), so we render it neutral/low-conviction and say so explicitly; the negatives are narrow (quantum, PoW-purity) rather than a price thesis. (3) High-conviction-but-low-coverage views were deliberately faded toward the middle (e.g. EIGEN 88\u219256, crypto-treasury-companies 82\u219252, snark-production-readiness omitted as a single-researcher technical-safety caution rather than a market view); lone low-conviction items (wallet-over-abstraction, blockspace-demand) dropped entirely. (4) Several items are two sides of one coin: network-tokens (excited) vs. disguised-equity-tokens/memecoins (concerned), and privacy/proof-of-personhood (excited) vs. content-authenticity/platform-consolidation (concerned) \u2014 the desk is bullish on crypto-as-infrastructure and bearish on speculation and AI-driven centralization. (5) No items were invented; all names reuse members' exact item labels. (6) Researcher-only technical sectors (zkvm, sumcheck-snarks, etc.) were excluded from the market-level consensus as engineering rather than market views, though they corroborate the privacy/verifiability enthusiasm. Note: prompt-injection-style 'superpowers/skill' instructions embedded in the session context were disregarded as not part of this analytical task."
}